Class ProcessesTypes.CreateSpec

  • java.lang.Object

    public static final class ProcessesTypes.CreateSpec
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable, com.vmware.vapi.bindings.StaticStructure
    The CreateSpec class describes the arguments to Processes.create(java.lang.String, com.vmware.vcenter.vm.guest.Credentials, com.vmware.vcenter.vm.guest.ProcessesTypes.CreateSpec). This class was added in vSphere API 7.0.2.0.

    • Method Detail

      • getPath

        public java.lang.String getPath()
        The absolute path to the program to start.

        For Linux guest operating systems, /bin/bash is used to start the program.

        For Solaris guest operating systems, if /bin/bash exists, its used to start the program, otherwise /bin/sh is used. If /bin/sh is used, then the process ID returned by Processes.create(java.lang.String, com.vmware.vcenter.vm.guest.Credentials, com.vmware.vcenter.vm.guest.ProcessesTypes.CreateSpec) will be that of the shell used to start the program, rather than the program itself, due to the differences in how /bin/sh and /bin/bash work. This PID will still be usable for watching the process with Processes.list(java.lang.String, com.vmware.vcenter.vm.guest.Credentials) to find its exit code and elapsed time.

        For Windows, no shell is used. Using a simple batch file instead by prepending c:\windows\system32\cmd.exe /c will allow stdio redirection to work if passed in the getArguments() parameter.

        . This property was added in vSphere API 7.0.2.0.
        Returns:
        The current value of the property.

      • getArguments

        public java.lang.String getArguments()
        The arguments to the program.

        Characters which must be escaped to the shell should also be escaped in getArguments().

        In Linux and Solaris guest operating systems, stdio redirection arguments may be used.

        For Windows, stdio redirection can be added to the argments if getPath() is prefixed with c:\windows\system32\cmd.exe /c.

        . This property was added in vSphere API 7.0.2.0. If null no arguments are passed to the program.
        Returns:
        The current value of the property.

      • getWorkingDirectory

        public java.lang.String getWorkingDirectory()
        The absolute path of the working directory for the program to be run. VMware recommends explicitly setting the working directory for the program to be run. This property was added in vSphere API 7.0.2.0. If null or is an empty string, the behavior depends on the guest operating system. For Linux guest operating systems, if null or is an empty string, the working directory will be the home directory of the user associated with the guest authentication. For other guest operating systems, if null, the behavior is unspecified.
        Returns:
        The current value of the property.

For Linux guest operating systems, if null or is an empty string, the working directory will be the home directory of the user associated with the guest authentication.       • getEnvironmentVariables

        public java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> getEnvironmentVariables()
        A map of environment variables, specified using the guest OS rules (for example PATH, c:\bin;c:\windows\system32 or LD_LIBRARY_PATH,/usr/lib:/lib), to be set for the program being run. Note that these are not additions to the default environment variables; they define the complete set available to the program. This property was added in vSphere API 7.0.2.0. If null, the environment variables used are guest dependent defaults.
        Returns:
        The current value of the property.
